The '''Anakeion''' or '''Anacaeum''' (from the Greek {{lang|grc|Ἀνάκειον}}), also known as the Sanctuary of the [[Dioskouroi]], was a temple in [[Athens]], which was situated neared the [[Acropolis]] and dedicated to [[Castor and Pollux]].<ref name="PalagiaPollitt1999">{{cite book|author1=Olga Palagia|author2=J. J. Pollitt|title=Personal Styles in Greek Sculpture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7qSsh7agZxEC|accessdate=15 January 2013|date=21 January 1999|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-65738-9}}</ref>{{RP|20}}

== Name and location ==
[[File:Peter Paul Rubens - Rape of the Daughters of Leucippus - WGA20299.jpg|thumb|300px|right|The Rape of the Daughters of Leucippus by [[Peter Paul Rubens]]. [[Alte Pinakothek]]]]

The name of the temple derives from the Greek {{lang|grc|Ἄνακες}} (an archaic form of {{lang|grc|[[Anax|ἄνακτες]]}}, "lords" or "kings"), the title by which the Dioskouroi, Castor and Pollux, twin sons of [[Zeus]] and [[Leda (mythology)|Leda]], were commonly known in [[Attica]].<ref name=OCD>{{cite book|title=The Oxford Classical Dictionary|year=2003|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=0198606419|edition=3|editor=Hornblower, Simon}}</ref>{{RP|80&ndash;81}}

The Old Agora, the predecessor of the [[Ancient Agora of Athens|Classical Agora]], was used in the fifth century and before as a rallying point, and references in [[Andocides|Andokides]] and [[Thucydides]] to musters at the Anakeion in 415 and 411 BCE have led scholars to conclude that the Anakeion may have lain within the vicinity of the Old Agora, perhaps to the east of the Acropolis.<ref name=Robertson>{{cite journal|last=Robertson|first=Noel|title=The City Center of Archaic Athens|journal=Hesperia: The Journal of the American School of Classical Studies at Athens|date=Jul–Sep 1998|volume=67|issue=3|pages=283&ndash;302|jstor=2668475}}</ref>{{RP|295&ndash;297}}{{refn|group="nb"|The position of the Old Agora is disputed, and it may instead have lain north or north-east of the Acropolis.<ref name=Robertson />{{RP|287&ndash;286}}}}

== Decoration ==

The decoration of the Anakeion, according to [[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], fell to [[Micon|Mikon]] and [[Polygnotos]]. The former depicted the [[Argonauts]], the followers of [[Jason]], with particular attention to [[Acastus|Akastos]] and his horses. Polygnotos depicted the ''Rape of the Leukippides'': the forcible abduction and marriage of [[Phoebe (Leucippides)|Phoebe]] and [[Hilaeira]], daughters of [[Leucippus (mythology)|Leukippos]], by the Dioskouroi.<ref>{{cite book|last=Jones|first=W. H.|title=Pausanias Description of Greece|year=1918|publisher=Harvard University Press|url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Paus.+1.18.1&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0160|author2=Ormerod, H. A.|accessdate=15 January 2013}}</ref>{{RP|1.18.1}}  This painting may have earned him his Athenian citizenship.<ref name=OCD /> {{RP|1212}}

