'''Shoki Coe''' ({{zh|t=黃彰輝|c=|s=|poj=N̂g Chiong-hui|w=Chang Hui Hwang}}; 20 August 1914 – 28 October 1988) was a minister of the [[Presbyterian Church in Taiwan]], erstwhile principal of [[Tainan Theological College and Seminary|Tainan Theological Seminary]] and director of the Theological Education Fund of the [[World Council of Churches]]. Through the Theological Education Fund, he is widely known for his coinage of the notion of "[[contextualizing theology]]," later better known as "contextual theology," which argues for theology's need to respond to the sociopolitical concerns of a local context.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Changing Face of Christianity: Africa, the West, and the World|last=Shenk|first=Wilbert R.|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2015|isbn=|editor-last=Sanneh|editor-first=Lamin|location=Oxford|pages=191–212|chapter=Contextual Theology: The Last Frontier|editor-last2=Carpenter|editor-first2=Joel A.}}</ref><ref name=":0" />
== Name == His name reveals several layers of complexity in his own sense of identity. He was given the name Chang Hui Hwang (or C. H. Hwang) at birth,<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Wheeler|first=Ray|title=The Legacy of Shoki Coe|date=April 2002|url=http://www.internationalbulletin.org/issues/2002-02/2002-02-077-wheeler.pdf|journal=International Bulletin of Missionary Research|volume=26|issue=2|pages=77–80}}</ref> a name he published under in 1968.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Joint Action for Mission in Formosa: A Call for Advance into a New Era|last=Hwang|first=C. H.|publisher=WCC Friendship Press|year=1968|isbn=|location=New York|pages=}}</ref> However, the name he chose to publish under in the 1970s and 1980s was Shoki Coe,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Coe|first1=Shoki|date=Summer 1973|title=In Search of Renewal in Theological Education|journal=Theological Education|volume=9|issue=4|pages=233–243}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Mission Trends No. 3: Third World Theologies|last=Coe|first=Shoki|publisher=Eerdmans|year=1975|isbn=|editor-last=Anderson|editor-first=Gerald H.|location=Grand Rapids, MI|pages=19–24|chapter=Contextualizing Theology|editor-last2=Stransky|editor-first2=Thomas F.}}</ref> the Anglicized version of his name in [[Japanese language|Japanese]], reflecting the context of the Taiwan of his birth under [[Taiwan under Japanese rule|Japanese rule]].
