'''"So mote it be"''' is a ritual phrase used by [[Freemason]]s, in [[ Rosicrucianism]], and more recently by [[Neopagan]]s.  It means "so may it be", "so it is required", or "so must it be", and may be said at the end of a [[prayer]] in a similar way to "[[amen]]".  The phrase appears in the [[Halliwell Manuscript|Halliwell or Regius Manuscript]], the earliest known document relating to a society of Masons in England dating from the first half of the 15th Century.<ref>{{citation |title=The Everything Freemasons Book |author=John K. Young, Barb Karg|page=179|isbn=978-1-59869-059-0|publisher=Everything Books|year=2006}}</ref> "Amen! amen! so mot hyt be! Say we so all per charyté".<ref>[http://www.freemasons-freemasonry.com/regius.html Pietre Stones, ''The Regius Poem'', last two lines], accessed 3 August 2014</ref>

The phrase has been taken up by [[neopagan]]s and they use it in a similar way in their ceremonies and rituals.<ref>{{citation  |title=Neopagan Rites: A Guide to Creating Public Rituals that Work |author=Isaac Bonewits|page=124|isbn=978-0-7387-1199-7|publisher=Llewellyn Worldwide|year=2007}}</ref>

